            <thetext>Our client comes in two variants for two different target groups. Even if they have the same locale, translations should differ corresponding to the variant. That might be a more formal addressing for the average user vs. a more informal addressing for a younger audience.

There are several approaches to that goal:

Hack (not nice): create different locales such as en_youth and en_elder. Advantage: done quite easily. Disadvantage: no rfc locale.

Bypass: use different keys for different output. Advantage: done quite easily. Disadvantage: Much overhead on implementation

Elegant solution (ok, I am biased): Have a variant-specific subfolder within the translation folder. The compile would search for the translation file within the subfolder for the current variant and - if none is found - would fall back to the default translation file.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
